# ANOMALY DETECTÄ°ON and SPLÄ°T

df <- data
df$month <- paste(df$month, "01", sep="-")
df$month <- as.Date(df$month,format="%Y-%m-%d")
df <- df %>% select(month,rate)
df <- as_tibble(df)
class(df)
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"
head(df)
## # A tibble: 6 Ã 2
##   month       rate
##   <date>     <dbl>
## 1 1972-01-01  11.6
## 2 1972-02-01  11.5
## 3 1972-03-01  10.7
## 4 1972-04-01   9.2
## 5 1972-05-01   9.3
## 6 1972-06-01  11.8
df %>% 
  time_decompose(rate, method = "stl", frequency = "auto", trend = "auto") %>%
  anomalize(remainder, method = "gesd", alpha = 0.05, max_anoms = 0.2) %>%
  plot_anomaly_decomposition()



plots show that about 1975, 1983, and 2021 include most of the outliers

df %>% 
  time_decompose(rate) %>%
  anomalize(remainder,alpha=0.5) %>%
  time_recompose() %>%
  plot_anomalies(time_recomposed = TRUE, ncol = 3, alpha_dots = 0.5)


Anomaly Detection and Plotting the detected anomalies are almost similar to what we saw above with Time Series Decomposition. Itâs just that decomposed components after anomaly detection are recomposed back with time_recompose() and plotted with plot_anomalies(). The package itself automatically takes care of a lot of parameter settings like index, frequency, and trend, making it easier to run anomaly detection out of the box with less prior expertise in the same domain

df %>% 
  time_decompose(rate) %>%
  anomalize(remainder) %>%
  time_recompose() %>%

after applying the box-cox transformation, the transformed series is not stationary. Letâs look at ACF AND PACF of the series

ACF AND PACF

acf <- ggAcf(train2,lag.max = 60,main = "ACF of Data")
pacf <- ggPacf(train2,lag.max = 60,main = "PACF of DATA")
grid.arrange(acf,pacf, nrow = 1)


ACF shows slow decay. This is an indicator of nonstationary. We cannot interpret PACF
KPSS

kpss.test(train2,c("Level"))
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  train2
## KPSS Level = 2.6486, Truncation lag parameter = 6, p-value = 0.01


The p-value of the KPSS test is 0.01, which is less than 0.05, so we have enough evidence to conclude that âthe series is not stationary.â

kpss.test(train2,null=c("Trend"))
## 
##  KPSS Test for Trend Stationarity
## 
## data:  train2
## KPSS Trend = 0.33555, Truncation lag parameter = 6, p-value = 0.01


The p-value of the KPSS test for trend is 0.01, which is less than 0.05, so we have enough evidence to conclude that âthe series has a stochastic trend.â

PP

pp.test(train2)
## 
##  Phillips-Perron Unit Root Test
## 
## data:  train2
## Dickey-Fuller Z(alpha) = -15.946, Truncation lag parameter = 6, p-value
## = 0.2202
## alternative hypothesis: stationary


Since p value is greater than Î±=0.05 , we fail to reject H0 . It means that we donât have enough evidence to claim that we have a stationary system

## Detection of Serial correlation

ggAcf(as.vector(r),main="ACF of the Residuals",lag = 48)+theme_minimal()


In the ACF, almost all spikes are in the WN band which shows that there is no serial correlation in the residuals to be sure, we have to apply formal test

There are three tests used for detecting serial correlation among residuals. For all tests, we have the following hypothesis
H0: there is no serial correlation of any order up to p p1=â¦.=pp=0 H1: there is a serial correlation up to p / Ïiâ 0

library(lmtest)
library(TSA)


### Breusch-Godfrey Test

m = lm(r ~ 1+zlag(r))
bgtest(m,order=12)
## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 12
## 
## data:  m
## LM test = 14.194, df = 12, p-value = 0.2885


Since p value is greater than alpha, we have 95% confident that the residuals of the model are uncorrelated, according to results of Breusch-Godfrey Test.
### Box-Ljung Test

Box.test(r,lag=12,type = c("Ljung-Box"))
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  r
## X-squared = 17.511, df = 12, p-value = 0.1314


Since p value is greater than alpha, we have 95% confident that the residuals of the model are uncorrelated, according to results of Box-Ljung Test
### Box-Pierce Test

Box.test(r,lag=12,type = c("Box-Pierce"))
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  r
## X-squared = 17.291, df = 12, p-value = 0.139


Since p value is greater than alpha, we have 95% confident that the residuals of the model are uncorrelated, according to results of Box-Pierce Test
## Heteroscedasticity Test

rr=r^2
g1<-ggAcf(as.vector(rr))+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("ACF of Squared Residuals")
g2<-ggPacf(as.vector(rr))+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("PACF of Squared Residuals") 
grid.arrange(g1,g2,ncol=2)


Both plots shows that almost all spikes are in of the white noise bands that is an indication of homoscedasticity. To be sure, let us apply formal test
### Engleâs ARCH Test

#install.packages("FinTS")
library(FinTS)
ArchTest(r)
## 
##  ARCH LM-test; Null hypothesis: no ARCH effects
## 
## data:  r
## Chi-squared = 9.865, df = 12, p-value = 0.6278


Since ARCH Engleâs Test yields p-value > 0.05, it can be concluded that there is no Heteroscedasticity problem.
